The new filter surfaces introduce unvalidated string inputs across both Python and TypeScript FFI boundaries, violating the repository's explicit validation invariant. The core functionality may otherwise work, but these public binding paths should reject invalid strings consistently before the patch is considered correct.

Full review comments:

- [P2] Validate Python search filter strings before dispatch — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-py/src/lib.rs:545-550
  When a Python caller supplies `SearchFilter(source_type=...)`, `kind`, or `status` containing an embedded NUL, these new FFI strings bypass `validate_ffi_string_py` and are sent into the engine, unlike the query and write fields. This violates the binding invariant that every string crossing the FFI is rejected before storage/transactions, so validate each optional string before constructing `RustSearchFilter`.

- [P2] Validate TypeScript search filter strings before dispatch — /home/coreyt/projects/fathomdb/src/rust/crates/fathomdb-napi/src/lib.rs:665-670
  When a TypeScript caller passes `{ sourceType, kind, status }` with an embedded NUL, these new filter strings are copied into `RustSearchFilter` without `validate_ffi_string_napi`, while the module contract validates every FFI string and existing write fields do so. Please validate each optional string field before calling `engine.search_filtered` so invalid filter text is rejected consistently.
